      Confidence rating:
      








Walton's fortune is derived from a calculated 4 percent stake in Wal-Mart. The shares are controlled through the Walton Family Holdings Trust as well as Bentonville, Arkansas-based Walton Enterprises, the family's closely held holding company. He's credited with a third of the shares, which were held by the estate of his late father, John T. Walton, the second son of Wal-Mart founder Sam Walton.
The size of his inheritance is based on on Wyoming court documents that were unsealed in November 2015, a decade after his father's death. Half of his father's estate was placed in charitable trusts and his mother, Christy, inherited the balance. Share information is based on the company's 2017 proxy and Form 4 SEC filings.
The unsealed court documents include the couple's 1982 premarital agreement, asset values at the time of Walton's marriage and death, and a declaration of how he wanted the inheritance to be split. They show that Lukas is the sole beneficiary of any remaining principal in five charitable trusts that were established in his father's will. Tax returns for them indicate investment performance exceeds the amount they spend on charitable giving. The trusts expire in 2036. The billionaire isn't credited with these as he can't access the funds for another 21 years.
He owns 22 percent of energy company First Solar, according to the company's 2017 proxy. He has an 8 percent interest in family-owned Arvest Bank that's valued using the average price-to-book value multiple of four publicly traded peer companies: First Midwest Bancorp, MB Financial, PrivateBancorp and UMB Financial.
The value of his cash investments is based on an analysis of his dividend income, insider transactions, taxes, market performance and philanthropy.
Kiki McLean, a spokeswoman for the Walton family, declined to comment on the net worth calculation.







Biography

Birthdate: 9/19/1986
Family: Unknown, No children
Education: 
            
            2010, Colorado College, Bachelor's Degree
          
          


Lukas Walton was born to Christy and John Walton in 1986. He is the only son the late John T. Walton, the second son born to Wal-Mart founder Sam Walton. A Green Beret veteran who was awarded the Silver Star after serving in the Vietnam War, John Walton died in 2005 when he crashed his ultralight aircraft in Jackson Hole, Wyoming.
Lukas survived cancer as a young child. He went to Journeys School in Jackson, Wyoming and graduated from Colorado College with a bachelor's degree in 2010.
Before John's death, his parents purchased a Victorian house in National Park, California, which Christy gave to charity in 2006. She also listed their Wyoming home for $12.5 million seven years later.
Lukas interned at True North Venture Partners, the venture capital firm founded by his father, according to a commencement address he gave at his high school in 2011.


Milestones
1985 Parents John and Christy Walton purchase house in National Park, California.
1986 Lukas Walton is born to John and Christy Walton.
1999 Family moves from San Diego to Jackson Hole, Wyoming.
2005 Father John Walton dies in an airplane crash in Jackson Hole.
2006 Mother donates Victorian house in National Park, California to charity.
2010 Graduates from Colorado College.
2013 Mother Christy lists 2.5-acre estate in Wyoming for $12.5 million.
2015 Wyoming judge unseals court filings pertaining to father's estate.






